################## Pima Indian Women Diabetes prediction Project ########################################3

################# Background ###################### 
# In particular, all patients here are females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage. 
# In this dataset it is shown how many times a woman is pregnant based on the intake of Glucose, Insulin, 
# and whether the particular woman is diagnosed with Diabetes based on BMI (Body mass index/weight) etc.

In [8]:
# Attribute Information

# Preg :- Number of times patient got pregnent

# Gluco :- Plasma Glucose level of the patient 
#          (Normal :- Below 140 mg/dl, Diabetic:- More than 140 mg/dl)

# BP :- Blood Pressure of the patient (mm Hg) 
#       (Normal :- 60 to 90, High :- > 90, Low :- < 60)

# SkTh :- Triceps Skin fold Thickness of the patient (mm) 
#         (Normal Skin Thickness in Women is 23 mm.)

# Insulin :- Two hour serum insulin test (mu U/ml)
#            (2 hour after Glucose serum Insulin level should be between 16-166 mu U/ml)

# BMI :-Body mass index (Weight in kg / (hight in Meter)^2) 
#       (Normal :- 18.5 to 25, Over Weight :- More than 30)

# DPF :- Diabetes Pedigree function (Synthesis of the history of Diabetes Mellitus in relatives, generic)

# Age :- Age (Years)

# Class :- Occurence of Diabetes (Yes = 1, No = 0)

# Now we will use a small function which will calculate the mean of the given column and store it in a variable 'mean'.
# Then storing the value of that variable 'mean' to an array 'mean_array' since each column in our dataset is an array. 

def Cal_Mean(Col_name):
    mean=pima_df[Col_name].mean()
    mean_array=[mean]
    return mean_array
In [100]:
# Now check the condition in dataset if a '0' is present in a column, we will call the Cal_Mean() function and replace the 
# value of '0' by mean value of that column using .mask() function. 
# Here we are replacing 0 for Glucose, Blood Pressure, Skin Thickness, Insulin and Body mass Index variables. 

pima_df['Gluco'] = pima_df['Gluco'].mask(pima['Gluco'] == 0, Cal_Mean('Gluco'))
pima_df['BP'] = pima_df['BP'].mask(pima['BP'] == 0, Cal_Mean('BP'))
pima_df['SkTh'] = pima_df['SkTh'].mask(pima['SkTh'] == 0, Cal_Mean('SkTh'))
pima_df['Insulin'] = pima_df['Insulin'].mask(pima['Insulin'] == 0, Cal_Mean('Insulin'))
pima_df['BMI'] = pima_df['BMI'].mask(pima['BMI'] == 0, Cal_Mean('BMI'))

# Now let's analyze the outlier and distribution (Normal, Skewed) using box plot. 
# But since scale for each attribute is different and it is difficult to get the boxplot for all attributes in same scale
# we will use zscore function from scipy.stats module. 
# Formula zscore = (X -mu)/sig
# Where X = Score (Value)
# mu = Mean
# sig = Standard Deviation

from scipy.stats import zscore 

# Storing value of 'Class' column in Class_value array
Class_value = pd.DataFrame(pima_df[['Class']])

# Droping 'Class' column from 'pima_df' since we don't want zscore for our target column. 
n_cols = pima_df.drop('Class', axis=1)

# Applying zscore
n_cols = n_cols.apply(zscore)

# Now again joined the 'Class' Column in pima_df and store the value in pima_df_z
pima_df_z = n_cols.join(Class_value)

pima_df_z.head()

############# Step 7 :- Summary  ########################

# Pregnencies :- It is clear that as the number of times pregnancies increase there are more chance of getting Diabeties.
# But the graph is not normally distributed. 
# 56% Women have Diabetes who are pregnent more than 6 times.
# 64% Women have Diabetes who are pregnent more than 12 times.

# Glucose :- There is a clear difference in the amount of Glucose present in the women who have been diagnosed with Diabetes
# and those who havent.
# 25% Patients have high Plasma Glucose Level
# 68.75 % Patients have Diabetes who have higher level of Plasma Glucose.

# Blood Pressure :- No clear difference is seen in the two categories who have and dont have Diabetes. 
# 16 Percent Patients has Blood Pressure Problem.
# 27% Blood Pressue Patients have diagnosed for Diabetes.
# This shows that Blood Pressure might not be a good predictor of Diabetes.

# Skin Thickness :- There is clear difference is seen between two categories who have and don't have Diabetes. 
# Those patients who have Thick Skin have more chance of being diabetic
# 31% Patients have Thick Skin than normal.
# 64% Patients who have Thick Skin are Diabetic
# This shows that Skin Thickness might be a good indicator to predict Diabetes

# Insulin :- No clear difference can be observed between the two categories of Diabetes in dataset, because percentage of 
# high insulin serum level patients is low and also lot of outliers are also there. 
# 17% Patients have high serum insulin level
# 52% patients have Diabeties who have high level of insulin serum. 
# indicating Insulin serum Test may be a good indicator to predict Diabetes.

# Body Mass Index :- There is clear evidence who has more BMI Value are more prone to the Diabetes.
# 62 % Patients are over weight. Which is higher than ususal. 
# 46 % Patients who are over weight have Diabetes.
# Hence BMI can be a good indicator to predict the Diabetes.


# Diabetes Pedigree Function :- No clear difference between the two categories of Diabetic patients. 
# Not a good indicator to predict diabetes. 

# Age :- After 50 years higher the chance of getting Diabetes than below 30 years of age.
# 21% Patients are diabetic who are below 30 years old
# 47% patients are diabetic who are over 50 years old.

######### Step 8 :- Conclusion ###################

# Glucose Level, Skin Thickness, Body Mass Index, Number of Pregnency and Age 
# seems to be the good indicators to predict Diabetes more accurately.

# Diabetes Pedigree Function, Insulin Serum Level and Blood Pressure
# seems to be least useful indicators to predict the Diabetes

# log2 transformation of exponential distributed data results near normal distribution.

# IQR (Interquartile range) is higher for Diabetic Patients for most of the veriables.

# Dataset is not very reliable to predict the Diabetes accurately due to lot of missing values and outliers.
